Seasonal ARIMA models
E.g., ARIMA(1, 1, 1)(1, 1, 1)_{4} model (without constant) (1 - \phi_{1}B)(1 - \Phi_{1}B^{4}) (1 - B) (1 - B^{4})y_{t} ~= ~
(1 + \theta_{1}B) (1 + \Theta_{1}B^{4})\varepsilon_{t}.

All the factors can be multiplied out and the general model written as follows: \begin{align*}
y_{t} &= (1 + \phi_{1})y_{t - 1} - \phi_1y_{t-2} + (1 + \Phi_{1})y_{t - 4}\\
&\text{}
- (1 + \phi_{1} + \Phi_{1} + \phi_{1}\Phi_{1})y_{t - 5}
+ (\phi_{1} + \phi_{1} \Phi_{1}) y_{t - 6} \\
& \text{} - \Phi_{1} y_{t - 8} + (\Phi_{1} + \phi_{1} \Phi_{1}) y_{t - 9}
  - \phi_{1} \Phi_{1} y_{t - 10}\\
  &\text{}
  + \varepsilon_{t} + \theta_{1}\varepsilon_{t - 1} + \Theta_{1}\varepsilon_{t - 4} + \theta_{1}\Theta_{1}\varepsilon_{t - 5}.
\end{align*}

B shifts the data back one period. B y_{t} = y_{t - 1}
B^2 shifts the data back two periods: B(By_{t}) = B^{2}y_{t} = y_{t-2}
A difference can be written as (1 - B) y_{t}
A dth-order difference can be written as (1 - B)^{d} y_{t}
A seasonal difference followed by a first difference can be written as (1-B)(1-B^m)y_t

